    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.49"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">49</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>A Star</figDesc>
                        <p>AMERICAN REVOLUTION BICENTENNIAL 1776-1976</p>
                    </figure>   
                        <lb/>
                    
                    Stan Hathaway 
                        Governor
                        <lb/>
                    Peggy Simson Curry
                        Chairman
                        <lb/>
                    Charles "Pat" Hall 
                        Executive Director
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="italics">Wyoming Bicentennial Commission</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps">STATE OFFICE BUILDING        CHEYENNE, WYOMING</hi> 82001
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>September 27, 1972</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Doctor Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>It's been years since I worked at the <hi rend="caps">OMAHA WORLD-HERALD</hi> and so you probably won't remember me, but I felt I should write you after a very memorable evening spent last week at Crazy Horse with Korczak and Ruth Ziolkowski.</p>
                
                <p>As we sat and listened to a recording of your voice reading "The Death of Crazy Horse," a thought occured to me. Through all the years that I have collected your books--and I have all of them in first editions--I have never had the opportunity to ask you to inscribe a copy to me. (It was my privilege to know Mari Sandoz quite well. I considered her a dear friend and have all of her books also.)</p>
                
                <p>Would you be so kind as to write a few lines and sign them? I have some particular favorites and if you would do this on two separate sheets, I'd surely be grateful.</p>
                
                <p>The lines are:
                    <lb/>
                    From Black Elk Speaks, "It does not matter where his body lies, for it is grass; but where his spirit is, it will be good to be"</p> 
                
                <p>Then from the "Song of Jed Smith" I've typed some lines about the discovery of South Pass. I wouldn't ask you to write them out, but would you please just sign the passage?</p>
                
                <p>I'm Director of the Wyoming Bicentennial Commission, and we hope to do something meaningful for the Indians during the Bicentennial years. An Arts and Cultural Center has been proposed for the Wind River Reservation, and the Commission is seriously considering it.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>Best wishes and thank you,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Pat Hall</signed>
                    <signed>Charles "Pat" Hall</signed>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Doctor John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>University of Missouri</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri 65201</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
                <fw>2</fw>
                
            </div1>
